This is Daryl Lane and David Carson. We'll be talking to science fiction author
Theodore Sturgeon this week, completing an interview we began some months ago.

00:49.140 --> 00:55.980
Sturgeon, of course, has been a science fiction fantasy writer since the golden
age of science fiction, beginning in the late 1930s. Many of his novels and

00:55.980 --> 01:03.380
short stories are classics in the field, and his influence on writers who came
after him has been incalculable. Sturgeon is noted as a stylist, that is, as a

01:03.380 --> 01:10.440
writer whose use of language is both distinctive and remarkable. We asked him if
his style was natural to him or if it was a deliberate choice. It's absolutely

01:10.440 --> 01:21.440
deliberate. The creation of a style, you can go a long way in the literary
business. Steinbeck did it. Aldous Huxley did it. One of the stunning examples

01:21.440 --> 01:33.360
is Ray Bradbury. But you develop a style and then you stick to it. Pretty soon
you become imitable. That is to say, anybody with any real facility with words

01:33.360 --> 01:45.760
can sit down and write a pure paragraph of Steinbeck or, for that matter,
Hemingway. To imitate Hemingway and Steinbeck is very, very easy. And Bradbury,

01:45.800 --> 01:56.560
particularly, is extremely easy to imitate. But you don't imitate Samuel
Delaney, for example. You don't imitate, I mean, not by the paragraph. I'm not

01:56.560 --> 02:03.420
saying that you can sit down and write a Bradbury story or a Hemingway story.
That's a different matter. But we're talking just about the matter of style.

02:05.500 --> 02:15.940
And, yes, it's a very conscious effort on my part to be able to write with
facility in any of a number of styles. And sometimes they're first-person

02:15.940 --> 02:24.680
stories. And I write out of the mouth of the person who's talking. And not
everybody talks, you know, in a high literary style. That's what I thought

02:24.680 --> 02:33.520
Aldous Huxley for, mostly. You read an Aldous Huxley novel and Aldous Huxley
talks like Aldous Huxley. And old men talk like Aldous Huxley. And little girls

02:33.520 --> 02:46.220
talk like Aldous Huxley. It's a monotongue. All the words come out of all the
mouths with the same kind of cadence. And I don't consider this really top

02:46.220 --> 02:57.820
writing. Why I admire Delaney so much is that when he talks ghetto black, it is
for real. But if he has two characters discussing modern American poetry, they

02:57.820 --> 03:10.380
talk in the terms of William Carlos Williams or T.S. Eliot. And he knows. He's
got a good ear. He knows the cadence of this kind of writing. And I admire that

03:10.380 --> 03:15.820
so very much. That you can't imitate. And so I consciously do that.

03:22.420 --> 03:29.980
Sturgeon's style is often as important to the impact of his stories as character
or plot is. And he's been praised often for his attention to language. But he's

03:29.980 --> 03:37.740
not always satisfied with his work. One of his better known stories, Microcosmic
God, he would like to disown. It's based on a fascinating concept. A miniature

03:37.740 --> 03:45.000
world created by a scientist with tiny intelligent beings on it. The scientist
can observe centuries of development in the micro society because these

03:45.000 --> 03:53.000
creatures live at a greatly accelerated pace. And as the tiny beings achieve an
advanced high technology society, the scientist spies on them and uses their

03:53.000 --> 04:01.300
discoveries for his own purposes. But Sturgeon is not happy with his story.
Yeah, I'm not too fond of that story. Not because the idea isn't unique. It is.

04:01.760 --> 04:12.260
That was a brand new kind of an idea. But because it was so badly written. It
was the first science fiction story I wrote. And it was, there was so much that

04:12.260 --> 04:19.980
I did not know about writing. One of the most important things about people as a
whole, and if you're going to write, you're going to write people well, is that

04:19.980 --> 04:32.560
nobody's all bad. Nobody's all good either. But the heavy in there was the bank
president. And he's cut out of 100% pure cardboard. He is so poorly written. And

04:32.560 --> 04:40.340
that angers me every time I think of it. If I were to write it today, he would
be very dimensional. And there would be some good things about him, too. And

04:40.340 --> 04:49.300
then you could believe it. And the idea itself of the little people under the
dome was so overwhelming that nobody else but me apparently noticed how badly

04:49.300 --> 04:52.900
that story is written. More Theodore Sturgeon next time.

