06:33.100 --> 06:40.500
This is David Carson. And Daryl Lane. Theodore Sturgeon has always constructed
real, believable characters in his science fiction and fantasy. Which used to be

06:40.500 --> 06:47.100
unusual in science fiction back in the 30s and 40s when Sturgeon was
establishing his reputation as a writer. Many of Sturgeon's people are, in some

06:47.100 --> 06:54.200
sense of the word, misfits. They are searching for something. They're incomplete
somehow. And they're usually different than others around them. The characters

06:54.200 --> 07:01.800
in Sturgeon's novel, More Than Human, are good examples. Right. That work is
built around an idiot, a pair of orphaned twins, an adolescent girl, and a

07:01.800 --> 07:10.840
mongoloid baby, all outcasts from society. Many of Sturgeon's other stories have
misfits as their protagonist, too. We asked him why. Well, I think a misfit has

07:10.840 --> 07:25.300
a chance to be objective. And for one thing, he sees society as a whole from its
underbelly or from way off at one side. Essentially, it's not so much misfits.

07:26.180 --> 07:35.700
The key to what I write, I think, is loneliness. I learned early that you can
write about excitement, you can write about adventure, you can write love and

07:35.700 --> 07:48.500
sex and so on. And basically, in each case, you don't hit too many people. But
if you write about loneliness, everybody's an expert. I'm fond of saying that if

07:48.500 --> 07:56.520
you know some guy who collects pheasant feathers, and that's his whole
preoccupation, and you write a story that involves pheasant feathers, and you

07:56.520 --> 08:03.600
know what you're talking about, he's going to love it. But the incidence of
people in the general population who collect pheasant feathers is very small.

08:04.980 --> 08:19.900
But the point is that because you wrote to an expert of an expertise, you see,
you grab him. Now, what are people as a whole mostly expert at? Loneliness. The

08:19.900 --> 08:29.220
world is full of experts on loneliness. It's something that everybody recognizes
when he sees it. So, it's not so much that these people are misfits, it's that

08:29.220 --> 08:38.620
they're lonely. And I think that that's the hook that I can throw into people
the hardest. Sturgeon tries to counter this loneliness with love. He often has

08:38.620 --> 08:44.640
his characters lose their loneliness by experiencing love of some sort. But
readers should be warned that it may not be the kind of love they're used to

08:44.640 --> 08:52.080
reading about or seeing on the movie screen. Not always. The World Well Lost and
Case and the Dreamer are two of the stories that concern very different sorts of

08:52.080 --> 08:58.940
love. One of Sturgeon's best-known stories is a powerful statement on love and
compassion, though it's the highest sort of love given to the whole human race.

08:59.260 --> 09:06.300
The story is called Thunder and Roses and it was published not long after the
atomic bomb was dropped on Hiroshima. The United States has been devastated by a

09:06.300 --> 09:13.780
nuclear attack and the last American military installation that could retaliate
chooses not to. The reason is to save humanity, to give our species a chance to

09:13.780 --> 09:21.420
rebuild. Sturgeon talks about the story. That's a very interesting story. That
was written, you know, when the dust was still settling over Hiroshima. It's

09:21.420 --> 09:30.040
probably the first atomic doom story that was written after the bomb was
dropped. It was written in late 1945.

09:32.800 --> 09:40.800
And I wrote that with considerable passion. There wasn't anybody in the world
who understood what had happened except the people in the science fiction

09:40.800 --> 09:51.120
fraternity and maybe one or two rather forward-thinking scientists at Oak Ridge
and in the state of Washington. And for the rest of the world thought it was

09:51.120 --> 10:02.240
just another big bang. But in science fiction there, John Campbell had been
publishing atomic power and atomic war stories for 15 years before that. I mean,

10:02.360 --> 10:10.020
we all understood what had happened. Every single person who'd been writing or
reading science fiction understood precisely what had happened and what it meant

10:10.020 --> 10:23.920
to the world. Now, of course, it's become pretty much in the forefront but we
all saw it coming. Very bad. An ugly situation. Sturgeon says he gets a lot of

10:23.920 --> 10:32.420
