24:13.620 --> 24:21.480
won both the Hugo and Nebula Awards in 1970. Sturgeon is also convinced of the
worth of science fiction, and keeps up with his development and changes. We

24:21.480 --> 24:33.280
asked Sturgeon if science fiction is becoming more acceptable to the general
reading public. Yeah, science fiction is becoming the mainstream. Really, look

24:33.280 --> 24:41.600
at all the pictures that came out last year, for example, last summer, with a
heavy emphasis on science fiction. People are beginning to realize that this

24:41.600 --> 24:51.520
forefront thinking is predictive or precognitive thinking. It's at some moment.
There are a lot of people who would not recognize that 1984 was a science

24:51.520 --> 25:04.740
fiction novel until very recently. I mean, Kingsley Amos once wrote that the
reaction to the general public and the so-called serious critic to science

25:04.740 --> 25:13.460
fiction is, hey, this is good. This can't be science fiction. Or, hey, this is
science fiction. It can't be good. You know. And this is the ghetto that science

25:13.460 --> 25:21.960
fiction has had to grow up in. But if you can survive in a ghetto, you generally
come out strong. I think that's the case with science fiction now. But I stuck

25:21.960 --> 25:29.900
with it, not because I couldn't write other kinds of things, and probably do
quite well, because I simply loved the field and the freedom that it gives me.

25:30.840 --> 25:40.820
Sturgeon is also the originator of what has come to be called Sturgeon's Law. He
tells us how that came about. Oh, that came about sometime in the 50s, and I

25:40.820 --> 25:51.560
can't remember exactly where it was, but it was at a science fiction convention,
and there was somebody who came to, you know, some people like to make an impact

25:51.560 --> 26:02.060
by getting a whole bunch of people who like a particular thing and coming up and
tearing it all to pieces. And he'd done his homework. He got a copy of every

26:02.060 --> 26:10.660
magazine that was in the hotel newsstand and every book, and they apparently
spent all night leafing through them. And he had a whole forearm full of books

26:10.660 --> 26:22.220
and magazines with bookmarks in them. And he convulsed the audience there for
about 40 minutes with examples of some of the worst syntax, some of the dumbest

26:22.220 --> 26:32.880
dialogue, some of the most improbable science, and so on, which in those days,
science fiction was a whole lot of it. And then he said to me right on stage,

26:32.960 --> 26:43.260
will you or will you not concede that this science fiction is 90% crap? And I
answered, I had this rush of brains to the head, and I answered him by saying,

26:43.600 --> 26:53.380
yes, but that's only because 90% of everything is crap, which quite took the
wind out of his sails. Then I was able to go on and develop the idea, which is

26:53.380 --> 27:02.980
only true, that science fiction has been in the ghetto for so long that people
say, oh, this is like Kingsley Amis said, this is science fiction, it can't be

27:02.980 --> 27:14.980
good. And it was unique as a literary genre in that it was not permitted its
spectrum of poor and good. Let us say in the mystery field, everybody could

27:14.980 --> 27:23.920
distinguish between, let us say, Mickey Spillane and somebody like Nio Marsh or
Dorothy L. Sayers. There's a spectrum of excellence there. Some of these things

27:23.920 --> 27:33.100
are better than others. Same thing in the Westerns. Hopalong Cassidy is not the
same thing as Best Three Rides a Game. But science fiction, it was all, you

27:33.100 --> 27:44.500
know, Buck Rogers, Zap Guns, and Space in the year 2200. And nobody would have
twice on the fact to find that there was good science fiction and bad science

27:44.500 --> 27:56.020
fiction and excellent and poor writing. And that caused my response. But since
then, that's been called Sturgeon's Law that 90% of this is bad because 90% of

27:56.020 --> 27:59.160
everything is bad. The present company accepted, of course.

